          <p>A <strong>failed Order Block</strong> that has been violated. When price breaks through an OB (invalidating it), the OB flips polarity — a bullish OB that fails becomes a bearish Breaker Block, and vice versa. Often one of the most powerful trade locations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <h4>Mitigation Block</h4>
          <p>An OB that price has partially visited but NOT fully closed through. A partial touch respects the zone — it remains valid for another entry attempt. Distinguished from a fully mitigated (broken) OB.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <h4>Rejection Block</h4>
          <p>Formed by a candle with a long wick — the wick itself (not the body) defines the zone. Represents a sharp institutional rejection. Often forms at the extreme of a liquidity sweep.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <h4>Void / Propulsion Block</h4>
          <p>A series of OBs stacked in the same direction — a <strong>propulsion block</strong> — indicating consecutive institutional participation at the same price area. Extremely high-probability zone when price returns.</p>
        </div>
      </div>`
    },
    {
      label: '4. Order Block vs. Support & Resistance',
      content: `<p>Many traders confuse Order Blocks with traditional support and resistance. They are related but fundamentally different:</p>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="info-card">
          <h4>Traditional S/R</h4>
          <p>Drawn at pivot highs/lows where price has <em>reacted</em>. Based on where price went — not why it went there. Subjective, widely known, easily targeted by institutions for stop hunts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <h4>Order Blocks</h4>
          <p>Defined by the last opposing candle before an impulse — where institutions <em>placed orders</em>. Rooted in causation, not correlation. Precise, specific, and often invisible to retail traders.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>The key practical difference: <strong style="color:#e8eaed">S/R tells you where price reacted; an OB tells you WHY it reacted.</strong> An OB that coincides with a traditional S/R level and a liquidity sweep creates a three-layer confluence — one of the strongest trade setups available.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Precision:</strong> OBs are defined by a specific candle, giving a precise entry zone — not a vague "area."</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Causation:</strong> OBs explain <em>why</em> price moved — institutional order placement — rather than just noting where it did.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Time-sensitive:</strong> Unlike S/R, OBs lose relevance once mitigated. They are traded once — their power is in their freshness.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Lower timeframe refinement:</strong> An OB on the 4H can be refined on the 15M for a tighter entry, reducing risk and improving R:R.</li>
      </ul>`
    },
    {
      label: '5. Order Block Zones & The 50% Line',
      content: `<p>Within a valid OB, there are two key reference points for entry precision:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Full OB Zone (Open to Close of candle):</strong> The entire body of the OB candle. Conservative entries wait for price to enter this zone — ensuring the OB is actually being tested before committing.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">The 50% Optimal Trade Entry (OTE):</strong> The midpoint of the OB candle's body. The most precise entry level within the OB — analogous to the Consequent Encroachment in FVGs. Entering at the 50% minimizes risk while maximizing reward.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">The OB Wick:</strong> The wicks of the OB candle represent the outer boundary. Stop losses go beyond the wick — not just the body — to survive stop hunts that briefly pierce the OB before reversing.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="key-box" style="background:rgba(163,230,53,0.06);border:1px solid rgba(163,230,53,0.22);border-left:3px solid #a3e635;border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:14px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
        <span style="font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:#a3e635;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:600;">ENTRY PRECISION RULE</span>
        <p style="margin:8px 0 0;font-size:13px;color:#e8eaed;line-height:1.7;">For maximum R:R: Enter at the 50% OTE of the OB. Stop below the OB wick. Target the next liquidity pool or FVG. This setup routinely produces 3:1 to 8:1 risk-to-reward ratios.</p>
