    {
      label: '7. Common Order Block Mistakes',
      content: `<ul>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Marking every candle before a move:</strong> Only the <em>last</em> opposing candle before the impulse qualifies. Going back further introduces noise and weakens the setup.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Trading a mitigated OB:</strong> Once price has fully closed through an OB body, it is used up. Trading a spent OB is one of the most common and costly mistakes.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Ignoring the displacement requirement:</strong> If the move away from the OB is weak or gradual (no FVG, no strong impulse), the zone was likely not used by institutions — skip it.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Confusing wicks for bodies:</strong> Standard OBs use the candle <em>body</em> (open to close), not the wick, for the zone. Wick-based OBs are a separate concept (Rejection Blocks).</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Trading counter-trend OBs without confirmation:</strong> A bearish OB in a strong bullish trend has far lower probability. Require additional confirmation (liquidity sweep, HTF resistance) before trading against structure.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e8eaed">Not waiting for price to reach the zone:</strong> Entering before price returns to the OB removes the edge entirely. The OB is the target — patience until price delivers to the zone is non-negotiable.</li>
